    <header>
      <h1><a href="/piracy">Best articles on piracy I've ever seen</a></h1>
      <p class="postdate">2008-04-03</p>
    </header>

<p>
<a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/">Andrew Dubber</a> has just written the <a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/2008/04/03/should-i-be-worried-about-piracy/">best article on piracy</a> for musicians, called “<a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/2008/04/03/should-i-be-worried-about-piracy/">Should I be worried about piracy?</a>”
</p><p>
The other best article about piracy in general is “<a href="http://www.openp2p.com/lpt/a/3015">Piracy is Progressive Taxation, and Other Thoughts on the Evolution of Online Distribution</a>” by <a href="http://tim.oreilly.com/">Tim O'Reilly</a>, which is the origin of the idea that <strong>the real enemy is obscurity, not piracy</strong>.
</p><p>
Actually, the <a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/">New Music Strategies</a> blog is really on a roll, lately.  Check out these new articles:
</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/2008/04/02/how-do-i-get-on-the-radio/">How Do I Get On the Radio?</a></li>
<li><a href="http://newmusicstrategies.com/2008/04/01/can-i-avoid-the-internet-and-just-stick-to-what-i-know/">Can I avoid the internet and just stick to what I know?</a></li>
</ul>
